{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01RwPwJa49bHqH44HTTQYkQo","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The error is:\n\"master not discovered or elected yet, an election requires at least 2 nodes with ids from [pctxSyrBTbSuDK9a7UKayw, uw65j1kmT4OGHa6zbz96pg, qv2eV5KhRoKiZ5J04FvGsQ], have only discovered non-quorum\"\n\nThe node IDs are:\n- pctxSyrBTbSuDK9a7UKayw = es-cluster-0\n- uw65j1kmT4OGHa6zbz96pg = es-cluster-1 (gone)\n- qv2eV5KhRoKiZ5J04FvGsQ = es-cluster-2 (gone)\n\nSince we need 2 out of 3 nodes for quorum and only have 1 node alive, the cluster can't elect a master. Normally I'd use the voting config exclusions API to remove the dead nodes, but that requires a master to be present first—so I'm stuck in a catch-22.\n\nThe solution is to use `elasticsearch-node unsafe-bootstrap` on es-cluster-0 while it's stopped, which forces it to override the voting configuration and start as a single-node cluster. This bypasses the quorum requirement and lets the cluster reform.\n\nFor the Kubernetes setup, I should update the ConfigMap to remove `cluster.initial_master_nodes` (since that's only for initial bootstrap) and set `discovery.seed_hosts` to just `es-cluster-0.es-cluster`, then run the unsafe-bootstrap command to recover the cluster.\n\nThe tricky part is executing this in Kubernetes—I could either scale the StatefulSet to 0, spin up a temporary pod to run the bootstrap tool against the PVC, then scale back up, or exec directly into the running container after stopping the Elasticsearch process.\n\nActually, the `elasticsearch-node unsafe-bootstrap` command is designed to run when the node is offline, so I need to find a way to stop the process without Kubernetes automatically restarting it. Let me reconsider using the ConfigMap approach instead—changing `cluster.initial_master_nodes` to only include es-cluster-0 and restarting the pod, though that might not work since initial_master_nodes is only used during bootstrap. I'm realizing the cleanest path forward is to scale the StatefulSet down to zero, which keeps the PVC intact, then spin up a temporary pod that mounts that same PVC and runs the unsafe-bootstrap command, and finally scale the StatefulSet back up. But I should double-check if there's a simpler API-based solution through the voting config exclusions first, though that won't work without a master node.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1566,"cache_read_input_tokens":43704,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1566},"output_tokens":69,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"5b5a42fb-dee8-4f2d-8a98-4796cae8b0c0","uuid":"ea987775-2cf0-475f-b398-e48aa68f033a","request_id":"req_011CcQaJwnAj7udHCASs3g6K"}
